		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Lectio Divina</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Lectio Divina</b> is <a href="/wiki/Latin_language" title="Latin language" class="mw-redirect">Latin</a> for <i>divine reading</i>, spiritual reading, or "holy reading," and represents a traditional Christian practice of <a href="/wiki/Prayer" title="Prayer">prayer</a> and scriptural reading intended to engender <a href="/wiki/Communion" title="Communion">communion</a> with the <a href="/wiki/Trinity" title="Trinity">Triune</a> God and to increase in the knowledge of <a href="/wiki/God" title="God">God</a>'s Word. It is a way of praying with <a href="/wiki/Scripture" title="Scripture" class="mw-redirect">Scripture</a> that calls one to study, ponder, listen and, finally, pray and even sing and rejoice from God's Word, within the soul.</p>
